PORTFOLIO WEBSITE

Project Overview

The goal of this project was to build a portfolio site using HTML, CSS and JavaScript to showcase my front-end development skills as well as my UX/UI case studies that I've done.

My Role

Sole front-end developer

Tools

Atom, GitHub

1. Understand

Background

The purpose of this project was to be able to better understand the processes of what happens after I hand over my designs, and so that I can better understand the challenges and limitations of implementing a design.

Timeline

September 2021 - December 2021

The Problem

My goal is to become a T-shaped UX/UI designer - that means for me having knowledge in various topics that will ultimately also help me become a better designer. Part of that is knowing the basics of web development. Not only will I be able to communicate better with web developers in the future, it will also shape the way I design. Because I want to work as a UX/UI designer, the first step was to create my own portfolio website learning skills along the way and creating a way to present my skills and work to an audience.

Goals

My goal was to create a responsive website that will show at least one UX/UI project as well as information about me and how potential customers can get in contact with me - doing this by using HTML, CSS and JavaScript knwoledge that I have gained.

2. Process

Research

I began my my process by researching what other UX/UI designers included in their protfolio website. Furthermore, I also wanted to get insights into what recruiters are looking for in a portfolio. After my analysis I came up with the following things that I wanted to include into my website:

Hero Section

that will represent me as a designer

Projects

presenting at least 3 projects to my audience

About Section

that not only shows my background and skills but also my personality

Contact

so that recruiters or potential clients can easily get in touch with me

Ideation and Visual Design

I used the low-fidelity wireframes that were already included in the project brief as a basis for my own high-fidelity wireframes and adjusted them to my needs. With that, I could quickly decide on to my design desicions.

Color Scheme

Typography

I chose a color scheme that picks up hues of blue because colors in the blue family tend to have an overall calming effect and evoke feelings of trustworthiness. However, I still wanted to keep my page lighthearted and genial, which is why I chose a shade similar to periwinkle

Main themes for color scheme:

trustworthy

lighthearted

creative

genial

In juxtaposition to that, I chose Montserrat and Crimson Text for my typography, which both have a certain edge. These should represent the analytical part of me and my work.

Main themes for typography:

analytical

sharp

to the point

Implementation and Challenges

After having my wireframes ready, I started to implement my designs using a monile first approach and my skills in HTML, CSS and JavaScriot that I learned along the way. The biggest question during this process was, if my design was possible to create the way I imagined. I did quickly realize that my first desicion to use a contact form on my portfolio wasnt as easy to implement as it was to design. Learning about those different technical ressources that would be needed as well as learning about margins, paddings and break-points made me realize that I should also change the way I design, so that is easier to translate into web design. It made me consider aspects that I wouldnt have before and also find solutions to get what I needed (i.e. a way for users to contact me) in a simpler way.

User Testing

I tested my site with 5 participants to identify potential problems with my sites user friendliness. With their feedback, I was able to gain valuable insights. Overall, they liked the structure of the site as well as the color scheme, however, there were also some improvements to make:

Improvements

Navigation

There wasnt a clear visual indicator which navigational tab was active. I fixed this by adding a text underline to the active tab. The logo could be a navigational help to get back to the home page.

About Page

The donwload my resume button wasnt as prominently placed, so that it was a bit difficult to find. I added some space around it to make it stand out more.

Further Iterations

Additionally, I want to add more and newer projects later on, so that my portfolio represents my development as a designer. Also, I want to improve the contact tab by either adding another page or having the aforementioned contact form in the footer.

3. Conclusion

Learning about HTML, CSS and JavaScript helped me gain a better understanding of how to design for the real world. The result was a responsive portfolio website with information about myself and my work.
